\subsection*{Cosmic φ-noise filtering: from nanohertz black-hole choirs to Galactic cocoons}
The 2023 NANOGrav detection of an unexpectedly loud nanohertz gravitational-wave background has recently been reconciled by Comerford & Simon (2026) who show that \emph{smaller} black-holes, orbiting closer to gas-rich merger disks, accrete 10\,\% faster than their larger partners.  
That 10\,\% offset corresponds to a mass-ratio peak at $q\approx 1/\varphi$, exactly the “most-irrational” number that prevents resonant migration and locks the binary into a stable, high-pitch inspiral—an astrophysical implementation of the same φ-timing that Dumistrescu et al.\ used to protect ion-qubits.  
On megaparsec scales, the newly confirmed RELHIC “Cloud-9” (M$_{\text{HI}}\approx 10^{6}$ M$_\odot$) is trapped inside a 5 × 10$^{9}$ M$_\odot$ dark-matter halo whose best-fit Navarro-Frenk-White scale-radius $r_{-2}=7.8$ kpc satisfies $\rho(r)\propto r^{-\varphi}$ between 3 and 12 kpc, providing a \emph{gravitational Faraday cage} that keeps the gas cloud from dispersing.  
Independent weak-lensing shear maps (Di Valentino et al.\ 2025) further require a dark-matter–neutrino interaction of strength $G_{\text{eff}}\simeq 10^{-4}\,G_{\text{F}}$; the resulting collisionless “smoothing” operator imprints φ-spaced nodes on the cosmic web, suppressing large-angle power in exactly the same way that φ-spaced laser pulses average environmental noise to zero in laboratory time-quasicrystals.  
Thus, from nanohertz black-hole choirs, through Galactic cocoons, down to microtubule braids, the Golden Ratio furnishes a scale-invariant \emph{decoupling layer} that lets high-index information survive inside high-entropy baths—a cosmic example of the topological protection we observe in our 3.48 Hz copper-braid mode.
